      <data key="d5">1768911161</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Shannon Entropy">
      <data key="d0">Shannon Entropy</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Shannon entropy quantifies the uncertainty in a random variable, indicating the average amount of information produced by a stochastic source of data.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-3f2b9c7716a8cfdb253e66aff0aa4394</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911161</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Kullback-Leibler Divergence">
      <data key="d0">Kullback-Leibler Divergence</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Kullback-Leibler divergence measures how one probability distribution diverges from a second expected distribution.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-3f2b9c7716a8cfdb253e66aff0aa4394</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911162</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Hessian Matrix">
      <data key="d0">Hessian Matrix</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The Hessian matrix is a square matrix of second-order partial derivatives of a scalar-valued function, often used in optimization.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-3f2b9c7716a8cfdb253e66aff0aa4394</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911162</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Jacobian Matrix">
      <data key="d0">Jacobian Matrix</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The Jacobian matrix consists of all first-order partial derivatives of a vector-valued function, representing the rate of change of the function.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-3f2b9c7716a8cfdb253e66aff0aa4394</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911162</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Gradient">
      <data key="d0">Gradient</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The gradient is a vector that contains the partial derivatives of a scalar function, indicating the direction and rate of fastest increase.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-3f2b9c7716a8cfdb253e66aff0aa4394</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911162</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Derivative">
      <data key="d0">Derivative</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The derivative measures how a function changes as its input changes, representing the slope of the function at any point.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-3f2b9c7716a8cfdb253e66aff0aa4394</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911162</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="3-D Tensor">
      <data key="d0">3-D Tensor</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">A 3-D tensor is a mathematical object that generalizes scalars (0-D), vectors (1-D), and matrices (2-D) to higher dimensions, critical in various mathematical computations.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-3f2b9c7716a8cfdb253e66aff0aa4394</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911162</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Tensor Derivatives">
      <data key="d0">Tensor Derivatives</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Tensor derivatives involve the derivation of tensor components with respect to other variables, essential in advanced calculus and physics.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-3f2b9c7716a8cfdb253e66aff0aa4394</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911162</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Definite Integral">
      <data key="d0">Definite Integral</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The definite integral represents the area under a curve over a specified interval and is a central concept in calculus.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-3f2b9c7716a8cfdb253e66aff0aa4394</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911162</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Natural Logarithm">
      <data key="d0">Natural Logarithm</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The natural logarithm is the logarithm to the base of the mathematical constant e, widely used in mathematics and applied sciences.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-3f2b9c7716a8cfdb253e66aff0aa4394</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911162</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Logistic Sigmoid">
      <data key="d0">Logistic Sigmoid</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The logistic sigmoid function is a type of logistic function that maps any real-valued number into another value between 0 and 1.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-3f2b9c7716a8cfdb253e66aff0aa4394</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911162</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Lp Norm">
      <data key="d0">Lp Norm</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The Lp norm is a function that measures the size of vectors, which is often used in machine learning to calculate distances.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e325d64a50359748cfb47987a361fbb1</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911162</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Squared Lp Norm">
      <data key="d0">Squared Lp Norm</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The squared Lp norm is the square of the Lp norm and is utilized for mathematical convenience in computations.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e325d64a50359748cfb47987a361fbb1</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911162</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="L1 Norm">
      <data key="d0">L1 Norm</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The L1 norm, or Manhattan norm, measures the distance from the origin to a point using the sum of the absolute values of its components.&lt;SEP&gt;The L1 norm is a mathematical concept used to measure the size of a vector based on the sum of absolute values of its components, often a substitute for counting non-zero entries.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e325d64a50359748cfb47987a361fbb1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0403607cb7181d4a13a232d13fec9630</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911163</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="L∞ Norm">
      <data key="d0">L∞ Norm</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The L∞ norm, also known as the maximum norm, measures the maximum absolute value among the entries of a vector.&lt;SEP&gt;The L∞ norm expresses the largest absolute value among vector components, simplified for practical use in mathematics and machine learning.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e325d64a50359748cfb47987a361fbb1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0403607cb7181d4a13a232d13fec9630</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911163</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Linear Independence">
      <data key="d0">Linear Independence</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Linear independence refers to a condition where the columns of a matrix are not expressible as linear combinations of each other, essential for unique solutions in linear equations.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-e325d64a50359748cfb47987a361fbb1</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911163</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="University Students">
      <data key="d0">University Students</data>
      <data key="d1">group</data>
      <data key="d2">University students, both undergraduate and graduate, are identified as a primary target audience for learning about machine learning and deep learning.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-bd2a057016fddbfc53fb1a5ab4973351</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911163</data>
