    <node id="Cat">
      <data key="d0">Cat</data>
      <data key="d1">creature</data>
      <data key="d2">Cats are small domesticated mammals known for their agility and hunting abilities, referenced in the discussion of neural network connections.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-95ce81b8a88d7af76b627732161bfd8d</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911179</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Mice">
      <data key="d0">Mice</data>
      <data key="d1">creature</data>
      <data key="d2">Mice are small mammals often used in research, mentioned in the context of comparing neural connections to other species.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-95ce81b8a88d7af76b627732161bfd8d</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911179</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Eigenvector">
      <data key="d0">Eigenvector</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">An eigenvector is a non-zero vector that undergoes a change in scale when multiplied by a matrix, maintaining its direction.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911179</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Eigenvalue">
      <data key="d0">Eigenvalue</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">An eigenvalue is a scalar associated with an eigenvector, indicating the factor by which the eigenvector is scaled during matrix multiplication.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911179</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Matrix Decomposition">
      <data key="d0">Matrix Decomposition</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Matrix decomposition refers to techniques that break down matrices into constituent parts to study their functional properties.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911179</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Prime Factorization">
      <data key="d0">Prime Factorization</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Prime factorization is the process of decomposing integers into their prime factors, revealing universal properties.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911179</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Square Matrix">
      <data key="d0">Square Matrix</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">A square matrix has an equal number of rows and columns and can contain eigenvectors and eigenvalues.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911179</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Linearly Independent Eigenvectors">
      <data key="d0">Linearly Independent Eigenvectors</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Linearly independent eigenvectors are eigenvectors that cannot be represented as a linear combination of one another, crucial for matrix uniqueness.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911179</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Norm">
      <data key="d0">Norm</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">The norm is a function that assigns a positive length or size to vectors in a vector space, indicating their magnitude.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911179</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Mutually Orthogonal Vectors">
      <data key="d0">Mutually Orthogonal Vectors</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Mutually orthogonal vectors are vectors that are perpendicular to each other, having a dot product of zero.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911179</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Unit Norm">
      <data key="d0">Unit Norm</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Unit norm refers to a vector whose length is equal to one, making it a normalized vector.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-d0d3be7ce3dfb930212c12aac0c54ff0</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1768911180</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
